## Introduction
In this chapter *Template Parts *are introduced. *Template Parts *are the *Doxee Template Designer *concept for reusable document components that are not limited to the use of certain elements, especially text. *Template Parts *may contain one more block level elements, but may also be used inline e.g. for text, images, etc. Block level elements always start on a new line, while inline elements continue on the same line as their neighbouring elements.

*Template Parts *can be collected in so called *Template Part Packages*. *Template Parts *may also use other *Template Parts*. That is, complex structures can be mapped quite comfortably.

Template parts are often used for structures which are not supposed to change much from one template to another, like headers or footers. But it’s also common to define template parts which only include single inline elements, like a barcode, which should fulfil the same specifications in all templates and may be easily maintained later. With the use of template part parameters it’s also possible to define their content as dynamically as any content inside a template itself.

> Tip

If you find yourself copying content from one template to another more often, consider the use of template parts instead.

## Step by Step
### Creating Template Parts
In this example we demonstrate the use of *Template Parts *assembled in *Template Part Packages*. As the name already suggests *Template Part Packages *are collections of *Template Parts_*. These packages are actual files, saved using the extension ITX like any other *Infinica Template *files. `[9: In order to be able to differ between templates and any type of package file (template parts, styles, page masters), we recommend the use of descriptive names, like myName_templateparts.itx, myName_styles.itx or myName_pagemasters.itx on creation. It’s also possible to combine different package types in one. An example would be to have styles and page master definitions in the same package. In order to do so, the output configuration has to be set accordingly. Please consult the Doxee Template Designer User Guide for detailed information.]`

*Template Part Packages *increase maintainability by reusing components. Next to the actual functioning of *Template Parts *this chapter explains the difference between *inline level *and *block level *using a concrete example.

*Block level *equals the level of paragraphs. *Block level *elements are elements with a mandatory line break after them, e.g. *Block *or *Container*. *Inline *is the term for elements that can be used one after another without a mandatory line break. A line break happens, if two elements cannot fit in one row. *Inline *elements must be within a *block level *element.

Create a new *Template Part Package *using the *File &gt; New *Template menu or pressing CTRL+N and selecting Template Part Package. Choose any name you like and save the file locally. Drag a *Template Part *element from the palette to the *Template Parts node *in the *Outline View*. Enter inline_tp as name into the dialog which opens.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 15. Add template part*

To demonstrate the difference between *inline *and *block level *Template Parts and their use you are now going to create both kinds. Put the cursor to the *Template Part Contents *node of your new Template Part and enter the following text: This is my first inline Template Part.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 16. Enter inline content *`[10: Do not be confused if this text does not show up right away when typing. Collapsing and expanding the Template Part in the Designer View solves this problem (and so does a complete refresh).]`

Being familiar with *Infinica Template Designers *concept for the use of *Blocks*, you will have noticed that just text is entered to the *Template Part *without automatically being wrapped into a Block element. Obviously you just created an *inline Template Part*. For example, if you would like to put a seasonal salutation in a template part, it probably will be part of the common salutation and stands in the same line as the customer’s name. Of course, you don’t want to have a line break then. Therefore you need to refer to it on the correct content level.

To visualise the difference create a second *Template Part *and name it blocklevel_tp. Drag a Block element into the *Template Part Contents *node of the second *Template Part *and enter the following text into the *Block *element: This is my first block level Template Part.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 17. Block level template part added*

After you have created these two template components, the next subchapter explains how to use them, but before going there don’t forget to save your changes.

### Using Template Parts
Using a *Template Part *within a template means referring to it. First of all, create a new *Infinica Template *and save it to the same directory where you saved the *Template Part Package *before.

In order to be able to refer to the *Template Part Package*, you need to add it as an external resource. Right click the *External Resources *node and select *Add new … &gt; Infinica Template *or drag an *Infinica Template *element from the *Palette *to the *External Resources *node in the *Outline View*. `[11: Infinica Templates may not only include template part packages, but also page master and style packages. Which Infinica Template files share which component types can be configured via the Output Configurations node which is found in the Outline View of each INFINICA Template. Please consult the Infinica Template Designer Userguide for more information.]`

> Tip

Using absolute paths may cause problems as soon as the template is fetched from another machine or moved. Therefore always consider the use of relative paths.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 18. Add reference to another Infinica Template*

A dialog opens where you can choose any *Infinica Template*. Please note, that using absolute paths can cause problems by migrating the *Template Parts *to another system. After you selected a file, you can change the path manually via *Advanced &gt; Miscellaneous &gt; src*.

In order to create a reference to a *Template Part*, simply drag a *Template Part Reference *from the *Palette *to the place in the *Design Window *or *Outline View *you want to insert the external content. Then enter the name of the *Template Part *you want to refer to by either right clicking and selecting rename, by pressing F2, using a delayed double click or by setting the property *Advanced &gt; xsl &gt; template-name*. In our case the name is inline_tp.

Make sure to insert the reference on the correct content level, i.e. if the *Template Part *is inline; it is only possible to enter a reference to it on inline level, i.e. within a block element. In order to distinguish better, insert the elements by using the *Outline View*.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 19. Add two Template Part References, one inside the Block, the other one outside*

The content of the *Template Part *is now shown within the *Design Window*. To create a reference to the second *Template Part*, drag a reference below the block containing your first reference. Enter name blocklevel_tp to the *Template Part Reference*.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 20. Template Part References added*

If the reference for inline_tp is entered on block level the program displays an error message and the content is not loaded. Creating a PDF preview is not possible either

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 21. Error messages*

If you have inserted the *Template Part References *correctly, inline_tp on inline level, within a block and the blocklevel_tp as block element [`12: or in a block – nesting of blocks is possible`], create a PDF preview to see the content of your *Template Parts*. The content of both *Template Parts *is processed in the output document just like local content.

## Things to Try
- Try editing the content of your *Template Part Package *and watch the changes in the output `[13: if an external Template Part is changed, all templates referencing its content need to be reopened/refreshed to display the changed content. After the template is saved, it’s also possible to use the reload button in the toolbar. Also see the user guide for more information.]`

- Try creating new Template Parts and insert them correctly

- Try inserting a *Template Part *which uses images and/or bigger structures, e.g. a table structure using *Repeat *and *Condition*

- Lookup *Template Part Parameters*`[14: Template Part Parameters can be used like parameters or variable declarations for programming and can be referenced in XPath- Expressions with $variableName]`
